<h1>Visual QC help</h1>

<div class="jumbotron help">

  <p>This microsite is for visual QC of the output of the
  <a href="https://github.com/biomedia/dhcp-structural-pipeline">dHCP
  structural pipeline</a>. Users can flag scans as being "good" or "bad",
  and the site collects and display everyone's scores. The aim is to make
  it easy to do a quick visual once-over of the results.</p>

  <h2>How to use the site</h2>

  <p>Click "Log in" at the top right and either pick your username, or click
  "New user" to make a new one. Please pick a short name, like "JohnC",
  it'll make display of the tables neater. The site sets a cookie in your
  browser, so you should only need to log in once and it'll remember. Click
  on your name again in the title bar to log out.</p>

  <p>This site has pretty much no security: we are a small group 
  and hopefully passwords are not necessary.</p>

  <p>You'll then be taken to the "Scans" page, listing all the scans in the 
  database. Click on the first, and you'll see a set of images of the pial 
  surface of that scan, some tabs to change the displayed surface, and 
  thumbs up / thumbs down buttons. </p>

  <p>Have a quick look through the surfaces, make a judgement about surface
  quality, and click up or down. Your vote will be recorded and the next
  scan will be displayed.</p>

  <p>At any point you can return to the "Scans" page and check which scans
  you have scored, or reexamine any scans you scored previously. If you
  vote on a scan a second time, your second vote replaces your first.</p>

  <p>Click "Results" in the top bar to see a table of all the scans and
  scores. You can copy-paste this into Excel if you want to analyze the
  results yourself.</p>

  <h2>How to tell a good result from a bad one</h2>

  <p>Pipeline failures usually show as areas of flat or distorted
  surfaces. For example, white extraction in sub-CC00605XX11_ses-172700
  failed, producing this unusually smooth area in the centre: </p>

